description.text: This is a small decorative print designed to hang on a 3/4" shelf.

This was originally designed with the filagree like waves much wider and self supporting.  What I've realized with prints of that nature is that PLA layers will occasionally warp up near the "lip" when printing angled circular forms.  This is not the same as the drooping down caused by overextension over void.  This effect seems to result in a nasty looking deformation on the underside of such forms, and has caused my hot-end to knock a number of prints off base.  In this case, I modified the design to eliminate the issue by adding the back plane.  
Should be printed on it's side such as to form a squared off J like figure.

title: Housing for Super Had Sony Camera Module

description.text:
The sony camera module I bought from http://www.securitycamera2000.com/products/600TVL-SONY-SUPER-HAD-CCD-D%252dWDR-Color-Board-Camera-with-OSD-Menu-DNR.html had obviously no housing. I wanted a printable and somewhat aerodynamic housing for it, so I whipped up something in Rhino. Printed at 0.1mm x 1mm on an Ultimaker, it looks quite nice.
It snap fits together and has access to all connectors, for the video+power connector, the control board and that one I don't know the function of. Mounting is intended on a piece of plywood into the groove, glued with hotglue (for this revision, I did not like an external nut+bolt)

Take the .stl's and turn them into gcode. I used Cura with the 'Joris' plugin. Use the provided .ini file for cura. Adjust the settings for the PLA/plastic you use. This shape is limited by the layer-cooling time of 3 seconds. If you have less cooling or your top-corners are curling up, increase this cooling time. You will need more patience then of course. 
Version 4 has a little bit nicer screw holes, but if your printer has been calibrated correctly, the two parts will snap fit together. You can whip up your own without screw holes from the rhino file (unhide the goodies?).

description.text:
The Battleship Bismarck was the sixth German ship to be named after Otto von Bismarck, the father of the German empire.

She was the first of two ships of the Bismarck class along with her sister ship Tirpitz

Her keel plates were laid down on 1st July 1936 at the Blohm & Voss shipyard in hamburg and she received her commission on 24th August 1940.

She is most famous for Operation Rheinübung, a patrol to hunt allied convoys in the Atlantic, which saw her set out from Gotenhafen on Sunday 18th May 1941.

This operation led to the Battle of Denmark Strait which resulted in the sinking of the Battlecruiser HMS Hood, jewel in the crown of the Royal Navy, in the early moments of the engagement.

The sinking was a huge blow to British morale and led to the mobilisation of most elements of the Royal Navy in the area in a chase to catch and sink the Bismarck.

Bismarck eventually had her steering gear disabled by a swordfish torpedo plane launched from the HMS Ark Royal on 26th May 1941 and her rudder was jammed at 12 degrees port.

The final blows were dealt by HMS Rodney, HMS King George V, HMS Norfolk and HMS Dorsetshire the following day before the order was given to scuttle the Bismarck at 1000hrs on 27th May 1941.

Only 115 of the 2200 officers and crew aboard were rescued.

This is a scale model of the Battleship Bismarck as copied from Jack Brower's The Battleship Bismarck in the Anatomy of the Ship series of books.

With the level of detail available making this model was simply a case of copying exactly the dimensions of each element of the hull, batteries and superstructure in a Blender model.

I cannot recommend the book enough to anyone interested in modelling this ship. Indeed the series as a whole is excellent.

This done all that remained was to make the model properly manifold (as best as possible - some errors remain but these are easily autocorrected by Slic3r).

See the deformation at the bow and the non-existence of the barrells (model printed at 60% size) Modifications present and future

Only one modification has so far been added in concession to the limitations of my kit.
That was an enlargement of the leading edge of the bow to 0,1mm - which has so far been of limited benefit (see blue model below)
I intend to extend that to at least 0,15mm in the next version, though using a smaller nozzle (which I don't have) would probably help.

I also need to enlarge the barrells of the main and secondary batteries in order to strengthen them.

Some of the decks on the superstructure could also use a few nods to the aesthetic to overcome technical limitations in printing the strictly accurate...

100% size model

I cannot tell you how much time I spent fretting over the settings for this print, so in case you want to print it I thought I'd save you a bit of bother by telling you what I discovered on the way to the first successful print.

The biggest problem by far was that as it it rather long (~250mm) and towards the end somewhat narrow - a sharp point at one end and only a couple of mm at the other for a couple of centimetres the first x prints had a habit of losing all adhesion to the surface and being picked up by the hotend on the next pass and being waved around over the heated bed until I could press HALT.

See the mangled mess that the stern became

I could not for the life of me determine the cause of this apparent insistence on the part of my printer to cause the near-left of the print surface to curl up (this is evident in several prints) and I blamed this on several, quite innocent, factors before finding a better solution.

Support Materials

One of the first things that occurred to me was that the support material was usually the first thing to get snapped up by the hot-end and wrapped into the next layer of print.

Consequently I played around for ever with the distance-between-support-bits function and "sleeves" for the support etc. but this had no noticeable effect except to ensure a larger quantity of support material be available to be dragged into later layers.

Raft

I then thought that a raft might be helpful - separating the whole print from the print surface with a layer of support material but this was even less successful, indeed had the exact opposite of the necessary effect. I was left with a concertina-like mess of support material that peeled off the print surface with a touch.

Brim

What finally solved the issue was introducing a brim of 5mm around the entire print. While this could not stop the warping altogether it did at least keep the object stuck to the surface for long enough to allow a few more layers to print and prevent the hotend from actually picking it up.

I just had to avoid the temptation to rip off every imperfection in the first couple of layers that emerged - any wisping of those first layers is natural, unavoidable, and irrelevant so you might as well leave it as is. Otherwise you print that first layer three times before anything gets done.

Fill Density
I will also be experimenting with a lower fill density, as I believe that this will also have some effect - I've yet to prove that though!

description.text: Bracket to mount an 80mm muffin fan over top of the Megatronics v2 motor drivers to keep them from overheating.

To install, with the power off, and power cable disconnected from the wall, wire an 80mm fan permanently into the main 12v wiring block (the white screw connector block). Make sure red wire goes to red wire screw block and black wire goes to black wire screw block.  
Remove the two right standoffs from underneath the Megatronics v2 board, retaining the four m3 screws for later use.  
Attach the fan to the standoff as in the picture using two muffin fan screws used to normally mount the fan in a computer (screws are shown in the gallery pictures). These are quite coarse, and should thread right into the standoff plastic with a little work. If they are too tight, ream them out. Note: ensure the fan when powered on blows down onto the Megatronics board instead of sucking air away from it.  
Slide the standoff under the Megatronics v2 board and line up the standoff to match the original holes used by the original black plastic standoff. The Megatronics board should be level with the new standoff in place. Thread two of the original screws into the bottom side of the Spiderbot frame threading into the bottom of the standoff. If the holes are too tight to thread, ream them out a little bit or use a small drill bit just smaller than 3mm to widen the hole just enough for the screw threads to catch. If you can, repeat this for the two top screws, and thread down into the standoff. Do not overtighten or you may damage your Megatronics board.  
Since I did this mod, I have not had the motor drivers overheat- no skipping. I also think the blue led light underneath the Spiderbot looks cool....

This is a proper guard for the Cheerson Cx-10 Mini-Drone, it is intended to be lightweight whilst providing a simple and clean aesthetic look for the CX-10.

I've seen some other prop-protectors that I liked but they were not quite what I was looking for.

There are two versions of the light-guard;

  • CX-10-Light-Guard-Robust: is a robust guard that was thickened in testing until it held up to crash abuse well. It can still break in heavy collisions but is far more likely to save your prop if it does, having absorbed the most of the impact energy. In general use it have proven to remain intact and unbroken. Four of these will add around 1 gram to the flight weight.

  • CX-10-Light-Guard-Feather: is a lighter version of the light-guard intended to reduce the effect on increased battery drain that I noticed in use of the Robust-version. It is more prone to breakage but will likely protect your props none the less. Four of these will add around 0.5 grams to the flight weight.

I've printed it in PLA at 0.2mm layer height and it has printed fine.

It's designed to fit on the Quick-Fit X Carriage Thing 19590- http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:19590 And it will also fit on Prusa and Greg style X carriages. 7th-4-2012- Split and added Gear set on two plates for Cupcake and smaller build-bed machines. 11-April - Uploaded Sketchup Source files (sorry for the delay)
I challenge you to make one that works with 50ml Syringes! or do a fully parametric version in SCAD :) And a very big thank you to Greg Frost (and derivatives) for the wonderful work done on the Parametric Involute Bevel and Spur Gears script, without this, the gear set would have taken me a lot more time to make.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3575

An assembly video for the Universal Paste Extruder can be found here, giving you details of how to build one up - http://youtu.be/iiyEOKpz_b8 You can print with Ceramic Clays, Silicone, Sugar pastes, solder paste for PCB assembly, Chocolate, Frostings, Masa Harina, and all sorts of other foodâ€™s or pastes that can be extruded through a syringe. I set out to build a tank of a drone. Something that would not blow away in the wind and could carry a payload equal to its own weight.

Hardware:
1 x Pixhawk 2.1
1 x 3DR GPS
1 x 915 Mhz Telemetry Receiver/Transmitter
2 x Sky III Quattro 4in1 ESC
8 x SunnySky Angel 800 KV 2820 Motor
2 x 8000 mAh 4S Zippy Battery
1 x 1000 mAh 3S Zippy Battery
1 x FPV 3 axis Gimbal (for a GoPro)
1 x X8R FrSky Receiver
1 x X9 Plus Taranis Transmitter
8 x 12x4.5 Props

Legs
8 x 8 in 6-32 threaded rod (for leg support)
32 x 6-32 lock washer
32 x 6-32 hex nut
2 x 18 in 1/2in aluminum pipe

Motor-Arms-Chassis
16 x 60mm M3 machine screw
8 x 50mm M3 machine screw

Chassis-Legs
8 x 16mm M3 machine screw

Gimbal
4 x 25mm M3 machine screw (for mounting 1000 mAh holder, battery plate, gimbal connector, and gimbal)
All of these will need a M3 nylon lock nut.

Pixhawk 2.1 Mouting
4 x 20mm M2.5 machine screw (for mounting the Pixhawk 2.1)
4 x 15mm M2.5 nylon spacer (for mounting the Pixhawk 2.1)

Other Things:
M3 8 mm washers, silicon wire (8 guage, 14 guage), 2 Mauch 200A battery sensors (these are great and have connectors for the Pixhawk 2.1), several zipties, 5.5 mm bullet connectors, 5 velcro straps (20mm wide and 1 foot long). Arms are made from cylinders 35mm pipes I took off a stacking shelf assembly I bought from Hardor Freight. I would assume 35mm carbon fiber pipes arms would be better but for $23, you get 12 arms. They are cut to 10.5".

The 3D printed objects were printed at 100% infill in PLA. This could likely be reduced to save on weight but that is not really an issue.

CNC machined parts were from 12"x12" cast acrylic (~3mm thick) with 1/8" single flute bit. All CNC cuts inside the perimeter are cut using inside the line setting. The perimeter of the piece is meant to be cut outside the line. I cut acrylic with 0.2mm depth per pass and 30 mm/s speed.

If you build one, your first thought will be, no chance this thing can fly. It weighs roughly 5kg or 11 lbs. Outweighing the DJI Phantom by 4 kilograms. But here is the math. Each motor, with a 12x4.5 prop, has 2000 g of thrust. Multiply by 8 and that is 16 kg of thrust. However, the coaxial design is not 100% efficient. The second motor just speeds up already sped up air. It does save on weight of the chassis. So say its 80% efficient and we have a max thrust of 12.5 kg. Ideally we'd like to be able to hover at half throttle and she does. At full throttle she'll soar. Careful on your first flight. If the Phantom is a Miata, then this is an H1 Hummer.

If you need assistance or have questions, don't hesitate to comment.

Leg Assembly

CNC
2 x CNC Legs
1 x CNC Battery Plate

3D Print
2 x Gimbal Battery Plate Connector
1 x 1000 mAh Battery holder

2 x 1/2" x 18" aluminum piping (Lowes)
8 x 8" 6-32 threaded rod (Lowes in 12" rods)
32 x 6-32 lock washer
32 x 6-32 hex nut
4 x 25mm M3 machine screw and lock nut
1 x FPV 3 axis Gimbal (http://www.banggood.com/FPV-3-Axis-CNC-Metal-Brushless-Gimbal-With-Controller-For-DJI-Phantom-GoPro-3-4-Only-180g-p-1030046.html)
1 x 1000 mAh 3S Zippy
2 x 8000 mAh 4S Zippy

1.) Place battery plate between the set of legs. Notches should fit into the cuts on the legs. If not, file down one or the other until all 4 notches fit tightly. Direction does not matter as both legs and battery plate are symmetrical.

2.) Add 8" threaded rods through small holes in the legs (all threaded rods are below the battery plate...holes in the top of the legs are for connection to chassis). On each rod will be 4 nuts with 4 lock washers. 2 will be on the inside of the legs (under the battery plate) and two will be on the outside of the leg to hold it in place on the rod. The Gimbal-Battery plate connector pieces will attach to the middle two rods directly under the battery plate (see photo 3). They will be loose until the 1000 mAh battery holder is added. Tighten the nuts on the leg rods so that the entire leg is perpendicular to the floor and held in place.

3.) Slowly feed the 1/2" aluminum rod through the holes at the bottom of the legs. Twist the rod back and forth to get it through. Too much push and the leg will snap.

4.) Through the 4 holes in your 1000 mAh battery holder, feed 25 mm M3 machine screws. This piece should match up with 4 holes directly in the center of the batter plate. There should be a gap between the battery holder and the battery plate for a velcro strap. Insert a velcro strap underneath and feed the 4 screws through the battery plate (see photo 4). These screws will then need to go through the two plastic pieces you fed on to the threaded rods.

5.) Now apply the black metal plate that came with your gimbal. It should have 4 holes that match up with the screws you have in place. Use a lock nut to tighten everything together (see photo 3). Instructions for attaching the gimbal to this metal plate come with it.

6.) In the top of the legs pieces are two holes. Feed 16mm M3 screws through them (with head of screw inside) and on the OUTSIDE of the leg place the Leg Chassis Connector piece. This piece should have 4 holes (that will face up and match up with the chassis) and 2 that will match up with the leg. Apply lock nuts on the outside and tighten in place.

7.) Add the 4S Zippy batteries on each side of the 1000 mAh battery holder. These are held in place with velcro straps again. One that runs through the center on the battery and is parallel to the threaded rods. The other runs long ways across the battery. Both have slots for the velcro to feed under the battery plate to be loosened and tightened (see photo 5). Then add 1000 mAh battery and tighten its one strap down.

Legs Complete!

description.text:
This is a stepper motor mount for OpenBeam. The customization parameters include a choice of parallel or perpendicular mounting, NEMA 8 to NEMA 42 motor sizes (because I have way too many surplus motors), and specification of other beam/extrusion sizes.

This component is inspired by the Open-source optics project, whose goal is to radically reduce the cost of scientific optical hardware, by the Michigan Tech's Open Sustainability Technology Research Group.

OpenSCAD code included for modifications. Just print on your favorite 3D printer and clean up. For stability/strength, this part may need 30% or more infill. The parallel version can print without supports, but the perpendicular version will need some supports.

You'll need appropriate bolts to attach the motor, and 4x M3 bolts and nuts to attach to the OpenBeam.

You can get OpenBeam at http://www.openbeamusa.com/

title: Shotgun Mic Shock Mount - Easy to Print

description.text: This is an easy to print Shotgun Mic Shock Mount. It is designed to fit into an existing microphone clip base and turn it into a very effective shock absorption device. As you can see in the pictures you need to print two of the end pieces, one center piece and one mount piece. You will also need the base from a microphone clip (the part that threads onto the mic stand). I cannot guarantee that all mic clip bases are the same dimensions so you should measure yours beforehand...the mount for this model has a thickness of 8mm but can easily be sanded down or remixed for you application. The ends and the mount are then glued onto the center with CA glue. You will also need some rubber bands for the ends...as many as you need for your microphone weight/configuration. (Rubber O rings from the hardware store work great too).

description.text:
A remix combination of polysquare's 120mm fan mount adapter that "lets you mount a 120mm fan to the back of the control box / PSU of Wanhao Duplicator i3 (Monoprice Maker Select V2)" combined with Taxus812's MOSFETpad for the HA210N06 Mosfet Breakout Board with the screw holes enlarged to 3mm.

description.text:
Updated 2/19/17

Ever like the variable designs of FlatMinis, but the customization of Dungeon Dolls? Ever wanted more options? Look no further! Inspired by the aesthetic of GrumpyRobot's FlatMinis, and DutchMogul's Dungeon Doll system, come Trixster_98's take on the classic Dungeon Doll.

These handy embossed Armor chest pieces and Shields include insignia's of a sun/star, a moon, and a sun rise. They print great but be careful about supports. If your printer can handle it don't use them. They are a pain and time consuming to clean out. These are compatible with my other figures, and when printed at 200% the figures stand 55mm tall. You can also print at 150% which stands at 42 mm. These were printed at 150%. Fully customizable and modular, look for more designs to come in the following weeks.

These designs are fully compatible with DutchMogul's original Dungeon Dolls, but not with FlatMinis
Made in Tinkercad, printed on my Monoprice MP Select Mini
These shields can allow you to denote differing factions or party's in whatever you might use them for

note
The shields come in four variety's. Embossed with the sun/star, moon, sun rise, or not embossed at all. Embossed is -Rise-, -Sun-, or -Moon-, plain is just the normal name. Armor is the same

note
Expect to see more embossed shields and armor to come out as extremely differing shield/armor styles come out. I'm planning on adding more insignia's as time goes on, as well as adding these existing insignia's onto new armor/shields.
If anyone has requests of specific insignia's/shields/or armor styles send me a message with a link to an example (Google image links work fine)

title: Prusa i3 Aluminum frame - Filament Spool mount

description.text:
I wanted to relocate my spool to the top of my printer so I designed this. It's designed to hold one (or several) filament spools on top of the prusa frame mounted onto 8mm threaded rod. I designed it specifically to feed directly into the extruder (also mounted to the top of the frame). I also left the top of the threaded mount open so you can lift the whole spool off without having to dismantle the mount.

For the internal spool reel that adapts the reel to 8mm threaded rod please see my desktop filament holder here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2063287

For the extruder mount that is pictured: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2068108

I printed the prototype with 15% fill, although for anyone wanting larger than 1kg spools or multiple spools I'd suggest at minimum 30% fill (for structural integrity).
